  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Through FY2026 to date, the Department of Agriculture has $6.3B in contract obligations across 16,591 awards, with an average award size of $382K. Current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date), and obligations fell 33.8% year over year. Obligations peaked at $11.6B in FY24 and declined to $9.6B in FY25 before reaching $6.3B in FY26. The department’s spending mix combines large construction and food-processing contracts with significant investments in IT and transportation services. The top NAICS categories include Nonscheduled Chartered Freight Air Transportation at $672M and Highway, Street, and Bridge Construction at $420M, while major vendor line items show contractors such as KIEWIT INFRASTRUCTURE SOUTH CO at $261M and TYSON FOODS INC. at $157M. These figures reflect the agency’s simultaneous procurement of infrastructure, food supply, logistics, and technology services in the current fiscal year to date.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How did contract obligations change year over year?",
        "body": "Obligations fell 33.8% year over year. Fiscal-year totals show $11.5B in FY23, $11.6B in FY24, $9.6B in FY25, and $6.3B in FY26, indicating a downward trend in obligations through the current fiscal year to date. The current FY26 total is partial and reported as $6.3B."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Where are Agriculture’s contract dollars concentrated in FY2026 to date?",
        "body": "Obligations concentrate in transportation, construction, food processing, and IT services. Top NAICS categories include Nonscheduled Chartered Freight Air Transportation at $672M, Highway, Street, and Bridge Construction at $420M, Animal (except Poultry) Slaughtering at $406M, and Computer Systems Design Services at $309M. The largest single vendor obligation is KIEWIT INFRASTRUCTURE SOUTH CO at $261M."
      }
    ]
  },
